<br>
I propose the following simple model of pet-mob fights in order to help evaluate when a better pet heal might be necessary.  This is in a solo situation, but can be extended to groups.  I assume a single pet for the fight.<br>
<br>
It takes a lone pet <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Mob HP / Pet DPS seconds</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to kill that mob, pet DPS here including melee, damage shield, and procs.  Likewise, it should take the enemy <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Pet HP / Mob DPS seconds</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to kill the pet.  Whoever dies first loses, so in order for the pet to win unaided:<br>
<br>
HP mob / Pet DPS &lt; HP pet / Mob DPS.<br>
<br>
In general, a mob will kill an unaided pet sooner than that pet will kill the mob.  We can look at the difference as <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;the second gap&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, that is the number of seconds the pets life must be extended, or the mob's life shortened, so that the mob dies before the pet.<br>
<br>
Mages have four options for intervening in the fight in favor of the pet: nuking, healing, tanking, and chaining another pet.  For this discussion we will only consider nuking and healing as options.<br>
<br>
Heals close the second gap by effectively increasing the hitpoints of the pet, extending the time the pet can fight.<br>
Nukes close the second gap by reducing mob hitpoints, bringing the mob that much closer to death.<br>
<br>
A heal extends the fight by HP healed / Mob DPS seconds <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (i.e the pet can endure that many more seconds of fighting)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
A nuke shortens the fight for Damage Dealt / Pet DPS seconds <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (i.e. the time it would have taken the pet to deal the same amount of damage)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
Both close the second gap between pet and mob death.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> First Conclusions:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
The effectiveness of healing a pet instead of nuking depends largely on two factors.<br>
First, the relative magnitude, time, and mana efficiencies of the available spells.<br>
Second, the ratio of Mob DPS to Pet DPS.  The more relative damage the Mob does, the less efficient heals are as opposed to nukes.  In contrast, the stronger the pet is relative to the mob, the more likely heals are a better idea, barring the relative efficiency of heals and nukes.  Note that nukes may be limited by aggro, while heals are less so.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Concrete Examples:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> NOTE:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  At first, I tried to use a 57th mage with GV:E and the 52 pet heal as an example, but I could not find enough parses and references to come up with a believable DPS range for GV:E.  I would <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>guess</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->, based on what I remember reading previously, that including 33 pt. DS, BO3, and muzzle, DPS should generally range from 25-45 DPS?  Although that would be inclusive of more mages, it would also likely being biased against healing and in favor of chaining pets.  Could you give me some real numbers to play with, <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Cyricus</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->?<br>
<br>
As many of the strongest advocates of a super pet heal are epicked mages, and it is far easier to find numbers on the epic, I will use as my example an epicked archmage with specialization conjuration and common focus items, but no appropriate AA.  While not as inclusive, its makes a sharper example.  For the epicked mage, chaining is awkward and distasteful, and the clear preference is to preserve the pet.  If heals are broken for the epicked archmage, then they are broken for mages with weaker pets.<br>
<br>
So our hypothetical epicked archmage has BO4, muzzle, the 52 pet heal, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Transon's Elemental Infusion</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Shock of Fiery Blades</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  The epic pet has 40-80 DPS, call it 60 for now, and 4,000 hit points.<br>
<br>
How many seconds does one cast of TEI close the gap by?  TEI heals 580 damage, but the answer depends on the mob DPS.<br>
<br>
For a 50 DPS mob, it closes the second gap by about 12 seconds, about as long at takes to cast and recover for another cast of TEI.<br>
<br>
For a 100 DPS mob, it closes the second gap by only 6 seconds.<br>
<br>
What about the rare 60 pet heal, TER?  As it heals 900 damage, for a 100 DPS mob, that closes the second gap by 9 seconds.<br>
<br>
Barring resists, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Shock of Fiery Blades</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> will do about 1100 points of damage with a damage focus.  This is equivalent of 1100 damage / 60 Pet DPS or about 18 seconds of pet DPS.  That is, it shortens the fight by 18 seconds.  It also costs about 50 less mana to cast than TER, with specialization and focii.<br>
<br>
From the point of view of reducing the gap in seconds between the mob and the pet, nukes are vastly more efficient than heals.<br>
<br>
But then most mages already knew that.  What limits nuking relative to healing is aggro.<br>
<br>
However, let's compare the 52 pet heal to the 55th level mage damage over time spell, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Wrath of the Elements</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, which has more aggro than the pet heal, but much less aggro than a straight nuke.  Also, WoE costs about as much mana as the 52 pet heal.<br>
<br>
Barring resists, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Wrath of Elements</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> deals 800 damage in 30 seconds, which is equivalent to about 13 seconds of additional pet fighting.  To reduce the gap as much as <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> WoE</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, TEI heals 580 points / 13 seconds or about 44.5 Mob DPS.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> In other words, against mobs that deal more than 45 DPS and barring resists, casting <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Wrath of Elements</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> closes more seconds than than the 52 pet heal.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
How does <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> WoE</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> compare to the 60 pet heal?  TER heals 900 damage / 13 seconds =  69 DPS.  So for mobs doing at least 70 DPS, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Wrath of Elements</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is better than TER, and costs less mana.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> So what?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Except against weak mobs, and ignoring resists and aggro, nukes are dramatically more effective than heals for intervening on behalf of the epic pet.  The higher the mob DPS, the less appealing pet heals are compared to nukes.  Although aggro limits nukes, smaller nukes and damage over time spells can be used to manage aggro.<br>
<br>
When are pet heals called for?<br>
<br>
If nukes are being highly resisted, then you are likely soloing the wrong mob.  If aggro is highly sensitive, then heals may be prefered.  If the pet is low on life, must not die, but the mob cannot be burnt down fast enough to close the gap, heals are prefered.  Indeed, for most times during most fights, the only time a heal would be clearly best is when the pet is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;close&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to dying, and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Mend Companion</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> would be appropriate.  Pet heals can then be seen primarily as a weak form of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Mend Companion</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, which matches the various proposed pet super heals.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> What I ignored:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
I did not explicity take into account mana and cast times.  The original version of this analysis did, but was more complicated, and anyway heals look even worse.  The long cast time of heals makes them even favorable than nukes, as they take longer to cast and recover than the number of seconds they buy.  Chaining the two pet heals does not improve matters much.  I did not take into groups, but this analysis would be useful there, especially in the presence of enemy AOEs.  I ignore chaining pets, and players tanking for pets.  I ignore the desirability of class interdependency.<br>
<br>
I also do not address the question of whether nuking is a far more appropriate response thematicaly than healing, and whether healing is properly a marginal capacity for mages.<br>
<br>
However, if mage pet heals are intended to be viable spells against stronger mobs, then the existing heals appear to fall short of that goal<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Razamatazz Pizzazz</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Abuser of EZCodes</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
