<br>
What's required is an analysis along the following lines.<br>
<br>
What purpose do pet heals in general serve?<br>
What should one be able to expect from pet heals?<br>
Do pet heals meet those expectations?<br>
If not, how do you fix pet heals?<br>
<br>
What the advocates of the super pet heal seem to be saying is that they expect to be able to save their pets with a single cast of a pet heal, assuming they have the mana and time to cast it.<br>
<br>
In other words, they expect a pet heal about as good as mend companion or a complete heal for pets.<br>
<br>
Is this reasonable?  I still think the answer is no.  First, because it isn't needed, and second, because it would be too powerful.<br>
<br>
An epicked mage chaining existing pet heals can solo the dragon <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Yeldema</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, see: <br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://pub6.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showMessage?topicID=6565.topic">Be wery wery quiet, I'm hunting Dwaguns-How I Solo'd Yeldema</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> and other similar threads.  That is close to the top of what can be soloed by any class, and is far better than most other classes can solo.<br>
<br>
Clearly, therefore, a pet complete heal is unnecessary for a solo mage, who already has adequate tools available to him.<br>
<br>
One of the most powerful partners for a mage is a cleric.  One of the chief abilities a cleric brings to that duo is complete heal.  An ordinary pet can be sustained indefinitely using complete heals.  A pet complete heal would allow a mage to fight mobs almost as well as a mage with a cleric partner.<br>
<br>
Thus a simple pet complete heal is too powerful.<br>
<br>
In order for a complete pet heal to not be too powerful, it needs to be limited in a significant way.  Not only should it probably cost a lot of mana, but require an expensive component, such as star ruby, which is used for Banishment, the inverse of a pet complete heal.<br>
<br>
I do see two cases for improved pet heals.<br>
<br>
First, I think it is fair to argue that the 144 minute refresh timer on Mend Companion should be cut in half, without the expenditure of any new AA.  It is an extremely limited form of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Lay on Hands</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, which has a 72 minute timer.  I can see no way that this is overpowering or subject to abuse, as <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Mend Companion</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is an emergency spell.<br>
<br>
Second, I think it possible to derive from this model a DPS threshold for AOEs that would force mages to chain pets instead of either healing or nuking.  If such encounters are ordinary on the Planes of Power, then many mages will be forced to rely almost exclusively on a single tactic in those zone, which reduces choice and would make the game frustrating for many mages.<br>
<br>
Some improved pet heal might be a solution to that.  Another solution might be to fix pet immunities, so that most of those AOE's are highly resisted by the appropriate pet.<br>
<br>
With existing pet heals adequate to solo Yeldema, and existing nukes twice or more as efficient as pet heals, it seems mages do not need better pet heals.  Indeed, the model proposed at the top of this page suggest that those who wish to preserve their pets to the end of the fight should try dealing more damage instead, and depend less on pet heals.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Razamatazz Pizzazz</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
