<br>
The question is, are the heals nearly useless?  Or do they do their proper job adequately?<br>
<br>
Are the heals only intended to reduce down time for vested pets <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (epic, equipment, buffs, etc.)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->?<br>
<br>
If that is the case, then first, that is a pretty marginal role for those spells, and second, there is some disatisfaction expressed by mages.<br>
<br>
Are the heals intended to intervene during fights on behalf of pets?  This seems obvious, as it the purpose of heals generally <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (one does not usually wait between combats to heal if one can avoid it)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  If this is the case, are they good enough?<br>
<br>
This model shows that <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>if</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> you can nuke, then against most stronger mobs, nuking is better.  Since nukes are faster and more efficient than heals, the limiting factor appears to be aggro.  Heals are much less aggro.<br>
<br>
If heals are an aggro management tool to help intervene on behalf of pets, then are they adequate?  The idea being that chain nuking would get you aggro, but that alternating nukes and heals does not, and is better than simply pausing between nukes.<br>
<br>
I have found that against most but not all enemies I solo, if I so chose to, I can sustain a single GV:E pet through the fight by alternating heals and damage spells.<br>
<br>
So I conclude they are adequate for me.<br>
<br>
While I mostly choose to chain, I have the choice to sustain instead.  Chaining pets is more mana efficient, but takes longer, and allows me to solo somewhat stronger opponents, but at greater risk.  Sustaining pets takes much more mana, but is faster and safer.  It is a more conservative approach.<br>
<br>
Seems like I have a choice of fighting styles then, both of which are adequate, and both of which involve trade-offs.<br>
<br>
Seems balanced to me.<br>
<br>
If the purpose of the pet heal is to save the pet from death when the fight goes ill, then the existing pet heals are not adequate.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Mend Companion</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> serves that purpose.  However, it may not be sufficient.<br>
<br>
While I remain unconvinced of the need or appropriateness of a super pet heal, it is clear that many magicians would like such a spell.<br>
<br>
